Functions: supplementary
	For the purpose of the exercise of its functions the Agency may do any ofthe following—
		engage in or commission research;
		obtain and analyse data and other information;
		provide laboratory services;
		provide other technical and clinical services;
		provide training in relation to matters in respect of which the Agency hasfunctions;
		make available to any other body such persons, materials and facilities asit thinks appropriate;
		provide information and advice.
	The Agency may do anything which it thinks is—
		appropriate for facilitating, or
		incidental or conducive to,
			the exercise of its functions.
	The power under subsection (2) includes power—
		to acquire by agreement or dispose of land and other property;
		to form or participate in the formation of companies;
		to enter into contracts;
		to acquire, produce, manufacture and supply goods;
		to develop and exploit ideas and exploit intellectual property;
		to provide accommodation.
	The Agency may make charges in respect of anything done in pursuance of itsfunctions.
	The Agency is to be treated—
		for the purposes of section 28A of the National Health Service Act [1977(c. 49)](/id/ukpga/1977/49?view=plain "Go to item of legislation") (power ofcertain health bodies to make payments to local authorities in respect of theperformance of functions) (except subsection (2) of that section) as if it isa body to which that section applies;
		for the purposes of section 28BB of that Act (power of local authorities tomake payments to certain NHS bodies in respect of the performance offunctions) as if it is a relevant NHS body within the meaning of that section;
		for the purposes of section 31 of the Health Act [1999 (c.8)](/id/ukpga/1999/8?view=plain "Go to item of legislation") (power to enablearrangements to be made between certain NHS bodies and local authorities forthe performance of certain of their functions) as if it is an NHS body withinthe meaning of that section;
		for the purposes of sections 13 (payments by NHS bodies towards certainlocal authority expenditure) and 14 (payments by local authorities towardsexpenditure by NHS bodies on prescribed functions) of the Community Care andHealth (Scotland) Act [2002 (asp 5)](/id/asp/2002/5?view=plain "Go to item oflegislation") as if it is an NHS body within the meaning of that Act;
		for the purposes of section 15 of that Act (delegation etc. between localauthorities and NHS bodies) as if it is an NHS body within the meaning of thatAct.
	The Agency must exercise its functions efficiently and cost-effectively.
	The appropriate authority may direct the Agency to have regard, inexercising any of its functions, to such aspects of the policy of theauthority as the authority directs.
	The Agency must comply with any direction under subsection (7).
	If the appropriate authority thinks that the Agency is to a significantextent—
		failing to discharge any of its functions, or
		failing to discharge any of its functions properly,
		it may (after relevant consultation) give the Agency such a direction as itthinks appropriate for remedying that failure.
	If the Agency fails to comply or unreasonably delays in complying with adirection under subsection (9) the appropriate authority may, instead of theAgency, take such action as it thinks appropriate to remedy the failure.
	The disclosure of information to or by the Agency for the purposes of theexercise of a function which is the subject of an arrangement made by virtueof subsection (5)(c) or (e) or in pursuance of a duty of co-operation undersection 5 does not breach any restriction on the disclosure of information(however imposed).
	But subsection (11) does not authorise a disclosure of information whichcontravenes the Data Protection Act [1998 (c.29)](/id/ukpga/1998/29?view=plain "Go to item of legislation").
	Relevant consultation is consultation by the appropriate authority givingthe direction with each of the persons mentioned in section 6 (if that personis not the authority) to the extent that the authority thinks that theexercise by the person of any function he has is likely to be affected inconsequence of the giving of the direction.

Publication of information
	The Agency may publish in such manner as it thinks appropriate—
		information it obtains from any source;
		advice it provides to any person.
	But the Agency must not publish any matter—
		which contravenes the Data Protection Act [1998 (c.29)](/id/ukpga/1998/29?view=plain "Go to item of legislation");
		in contravention of an express restriction contained in any other enactmenton the publication of the matter;
		if the publication is not in the public interest.
	Enactment includes—
		any provision of or instrument made under an Act of the ScottishParliament;
		Northern Ireland legislation.

Commencement 
	Except as provided in subsection (3) the preceding provisions of this Actcome into force on such day as the Secretary of State may by order made bystatutory instrument appoint.
	Different days may be appointed for different purposes.
	Paragraph 3 of Schedule 3 comes into force two months after the day onwhich this Act is passed.
	The Secretary of State must not make an order under subsection (1) for thepurposes of section 1 unless he first consults—
		the Scottish Ministers;
		the Department of Health, Social Services and Public Safety in NorthernIreland;
		the National Assembly for Wales.
	The appropriate authority may by order make such provision as it thinksnecessary or expedient in consequence of the coming into force of this Act(including provision amending, repealing or revoking any enactment passed ormade before the passing of this Act).
	Unless an order under subsection (5) amends or repeals an enactmentcontained in an Act or an Act of the Scottish Parliament—
		if it is made by the Secretary of State it must be made by statutoryinstrument subject to annulment in pursuance of a resolution of either Houseof Parliament;
		if it is made by the Scottish Ministers it must be made by statutoryinstrument subject to annulment in pursuance of a resolution of the ScottishParliament;
		if it is made by the Department of Health, Social Services and PublicSafety in Northern Ireland it must be made by statutory rule (for the purposesof the Statutory Rules (Northern Ireland) Order 1979 ([S.I. 1979/1573 (N.I.12)](/id/nisi/1979/1573?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"))) subject tonegative resolution.
	The power to make an order under subsection (5) which does amend or repealsuch an enactment—
		is exercisable by the Secretary of State by statutory instrument but nosuch order may be made unless a draft of the order has been approved by aresolution of each House of Parliament;
		is exercisable by the Scottish Ministers by statutory instrument but nosuch order may be made unless a draft of the order has been approved by aresolution of the Scottish Parliament;
		is exercisable by the Department of Health, Social Services and PublicSafety in Northern Ireland by statutory rule subject to affirmativeresolution.
	An order made by the National Assembly for Wales must be made by statutoryinstrument.
	Negative resolution and affirmative resolution must be construed inaccordance with section 41 of the Interpretation Act (Northern Ireland) [1954(c. 33 (N.I.))](/id/apni/1954/33?view=plain "Go to item of legislation").
	Enactment includes—
		any provision of or instrument made under an Act of the ScottishParliament;
		Northern Ireland legislation.
